    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concept of free speech is closely tied to the idea of individual autonomy and the protection of minority viewpoints. The notion that government regulation of the internet infringes upon free speech is rooted in the First Amendment's protection of \"the freedom of speech, or of the press.\" The Supreme Court's decision in Brandenburg v. Ohio (1969) established that speech can only be restricted if it is \"directed to inciting or producing imminent lawless action and is likely to incite or produce such action.\" This precedent sets a high bar for government regulation of online speech, making it challenging to justify restrictions that might be seen as stifling free expression.",
